Dear Beate

Somewhere buried in this thread Wolfgang said

==========================
This goes back to Fisher (1925; Statistical methods for research workers).

In your application (where you dealing with pairs), n is the number of 
pairs and m is 2. In that case, you can treat ICC(1) values like regular 
correlations. However, if you do apply the r-to-z transformation, then 
Fisher suggests to use 1/(n-3/2) as the variance (instead of 1/(n-3) as 
we typically use for r-to-z transformed Pearson product-moment 
correlation coefficients) and simulation studies I have done confirm this.
======================

Michael

